Virtual Inheritance - Initialization

Assume Base1 is derived by Base2 and Base3, (and Virtually Inherits*)
	and Base4 derives from Base2 and Base3

Example:
	 ScavTrap and FragTrap both inherit from ClapTrap virtually.
	Therefore the Virtual base class is ClapTrap.
	And DiamondTrap inherits normally from ScavTrap and FragTrap.
	Therefore the most derived class is DiamondTrap.

    	The virtual base class (ClapTrap) is only initialized once by the most derived class (DiamondTrap).

	When you call ScavTrap(name) and FragTrap(name), the constructors of ScavTrap and FragTrap 
		do not directly call the parameterized constructor of ClapTrap. 
	Instead, the virtual base class (ClapTrap) is initialized by DiamondTrap.
	
	Therefore, although DiamondTrap does not inherit from ClapTrap directly, 
	the Parameterized constructor of DiamondTrap must include ClapTrap parameter constructor.

DiamondTrap::DiamondTrap(std::string name) : ClapTrap(name), ScavTrap(name), FragTrap(name)

If not the Default Constructor of ClapTrap will be called.

Why the Default Constructor is Called

The reason the default constructor of ClapTrap is called is because 
DiamondTrap does not explicitly initialize ClapTrap with the parameterized constructor. 
In virtual inheritance, if you do not explicitly initialize the virtual base class in the most derived class, 
the default constructor of the virtual base class is called.

